Sep 16 2009 	Writing from the hotel room now...	As I type this in the hotel room, I would like to explain that I am not accustomed to such luxury. To me it is luxury, to others is it not.---I am staying at this hotel for about 2 weeks. For the past 3 years I have been coming to Beijing, to see family. Although smoggy with disastrous traffic, I love this city.I entered the hotel with my cousin via taxi. There are two doormen whose job is to push the rotating door for you.That was strange...but awesome.The street level floor has reception and the bar. On either side of the floor is Chanel and Louis Vuitton. On the two bottom floors there are more designer stores like Armani. The reception staff was very nice and they spoke English very well. Of course if you cannot understand English with a Chinese accent, you are doomed.Their accents were not too bad, but I am used to it.If there is something mundane that a hotel traveler is used to and their is a staff person close, they will usually do it for you.Example, a receptionist pushed the up button for my cousin and I, when we were going towards the elevator. The bellhops bring your bags to the door. Mine were 2 heavy duffel bags, so they brought two people.The hotel is located 1 block or so from Wangfujing street, a popular tourist spot that has everything you might need. Immediately around the corner there is a market where you can buy water, snacks and shampoo. I recommend not drinking the tap water if you have a sensitive stomach or if you are not from China. It can easily upset your stomach. Boiling the water is fine though.---Still trying to recover from jetlag, I caved and ordered the Chinese breakfast room service.Also, I do not know what &quot;business casual&quot; actually is for the restaurants...haha.For 24 USD, it is quite a helping of food.Congee (rice soup), fresh fruit, fresh juice, chinese pickles, tea, dimsum and noodles.They even had little mini char siu bao!It was very good, although not as good as homecooked.I decided to head to the pool before my spa treatment.You sign in with your room number. If needed you can have a locker key to keep your things in. I was not sure how to dress when going down to the pool, so I just wore my clothes.Inside the locker they give you a towel, a bathrobe, poolside slippers and a few coat hangers.Before you enter the pool, you must walk through ankle deep water to clean your feet.A woman is inside the pool area to assist you. When you enter she lays out towels on a sun-chair, gives you a bottle of water and a magazine. There are also goggles if you need them.She spoke enough English to communicate the needs.The pool was a little cold, I will admit. Then again it IS 84 degrees outside....Although I do not know if it her job, I assume it is, she turns on the shower for you and dries your bathing siut too. I am used to using the bathing suit dryers myself, so I assumed the patron did it. But she said no no and dried the other half of my suit.--- If you stayed with me through this whole review, congrats!But joking aside, I really do like this place.If you are a business person or are used to total luxury hotels, this might not be for you.I am the kind of person who does not need an extra sitting room.	
