Dec 3 2005	One of the top hotels in China	I stayed at the Peninsula Palace earlier this year and it was great although service could be better.Location: I always thought it is adjacent to Wangfujing from the maps, but in reality you have to walk few minutes to reach it, and yet another few minutes to reach Oriental Plaza. From this point, the Tiananmen Square and Forbidden City is another 5-10 minutes walk. If location is paramount, the Grand Hyatt is better as it sits atop Oriental Plaza. The China World is also conveniently located atop World Trade Center with great shopping Center (and ice skating rink).Lobby: Opulent and grand with dramatic atrium and white carrara grand staircase leading to either business centre &amp; ballroom upstairs or the impressive collection of luxury boutiques and restaurants downstair.Service: Check in was swift, where I was escorted right up to my room, which is quite personal considering the size of the hotel (500 plus rooms). Concierge, however, was a bit of let down. I requested a simple task to re-confirm my airline ticket to Jakarta but they could not find the phone number / location of the airline’s office in Beijing. They made several attempts to call the Hong Kong and Shanghai office, but I was told to wait. I even asked them to check the net for the address, but still no result The next day, I followed it up but still yet to be confirmed. At the end, I went up to the business Center and rent it's 15 minutes internet for 30RMB and found the phone details myself, give it to the concierge and straight away got it confirmed.You can rent DVD for free from a list of options. Mine took more than half an hour and a few calls to get it delivered.Rooms: There are no impressive views from the hotel. The Deluxe rooms (31 sq.m) are located on the sides (possibly could have distant view to the forbidden City from top floors). The Grand Deluxe rooms (34sq.m) face either the main entrance or the indoor pool on the podium with distant view towards Chang An avenue. Opt for Grand Deluxe rooms as they have larger bathroom with separate shower and bath and TV.Rooms are not as large (e.g Grand Hyatt Shanghai 40m2, Island Shangri-La HK 44m2, Ritz Carlton Singapore 50m2), but they are superbly furnished. Teak wood with rugs, mood lighting, comfortable sofas, plasma tv, personal fax machine, DVD players with some music CDs selection and great control panel by the bed.Bath: Grand Deluxe bathrooms are large, with small TV by the vanity and control panels by the tub. Bath amenities are not great, nor are they designer brand as with other top hotels. Restaurant: My rates include a buffet breakfast at Jing, which is located at the basement. Although it has no view / street frontage, it is still feel very cozy. The design is great especially the private rooms. The breakfast food is allright, but not superb: quantity is not great but has good quality.Facilities: Check out the 50 luxury boutiques (from LV, Gucci, Prada, Tiffany) which can be handy for shopaholics. The pool was closed at that time, but should be nice with glass skylight when open.Rates: When booking the hotel, should check out directly to the hotel's website as sometimes they have good bargain with rates down to USD 160, incl. bfast (rack rates are USD 340).	
Nov 29 2005 	Great Stay at the Peninsula Palace	I just returned from a six night stay at the Peninsula Palace Hotel in Beijing. The hotel is nicely located, a few blocks away from the Wangfujing shopping district and a 20-30 minute walk from the Forbidden City and Tiananmen Square.The hotel has excellent facilities including a pool / fitness center, a shopping mall in the basement, good room service, and a spectacular restaurant – Huang Ting. I stayed at this hotel for business and had a grand deluxe room on the club level. The club level rooms are about $50/night more expensive than the regular rooms but they include free breakfast, afternoon tea / desserts, and evening snacks in the 13th floor club lounge. Drinks, Internet access, and clothes pressing are also free and, in my opinion, round out a worthwhile upgrade from the regular rooms. My biggest gripe with the club level is the lack of authentic Chinese food and snacks – almost everything provided was too Americanized.The best feature of the hotel is probably the rooms with all their extravagant gadgets and amenities including a flat panel TV in both the bedroom and the bathroom, and a control panel next to the bed that controls everything from the TV and radio to the temperature and mood lighting. The control panel seems to have a motion detector built in so the lights on the display turn on as you move your hand closer…neat.If you don’t speak Chinese it is useful to have a card to hand to taxi drivers that identifies your destination in Chinese characters. The concierge at the Peninsula Palace has some of these with popular destinations printed on them. Interestingly, the cards don’t include the airport as a popular destination (the one place almost every visitor would need to go eventually!). My theory is that this is because the hotel is more than happy to arrange one of their comfortable but pricey limos for this service. Even if you do take a taxi, the doorman knows to call the more expensive 2.00 yuan/km rides over the standard 1.60 yuan/km ones…very clever. A few tips from my stay:1. Single men should be prepared to be approached about 50 times between the hotel and the Forbidden city by young women pretending to study English or just looking for “fun;”2. Do visit the weekend market to buy some quality arts and crafts at low prices;3. Don’t wear shorts regardless of the weather – it is bad form – I can count on one hand the number of people I saw wearing shorts in Beijing over a one week period (all misinformed tourists); and4. Don’t buy things from government-run Friendship stores or jade/jewelry factories included in itineraries to the Great Wall unless you enjoy paying 10X too much for merchandise. Even the trips organized by the Peninsula Palace include these annoying stops.Overall, I would certainly consider staying here again, but next time I might try the Grand Hyatt just to sample some of Beijing’s other hotels. The Grand Hyatt looks very nice and is located at Oriental Plaza, slightly closer to the Forbidden City and the subway.	
